text: Factor crowding is true in some cases. So for example, back in spring 2016, you had a massive rush from investors into level quality that led into the big rotation, the circular rotation of the summer 2016 from quality level into value. But you could see that in the prices, you could see in the factor prices, you could see this acceleration in price. That was a manifestation of a crowding. One of the indicator that I'm following and when I'm looking at factors is the relative performance of a factor versus its peer. And whenever you see a factor return accelerating versus its peer on a cross-sectional basis, this is most of the cases, the sign of over crowding or a sign of rush of investors into this factor, like a bubble, basically. And that happens, that happens regularly. If it's a matter of fact, I don't believe so in a way. I believe it's momentary, because at some point, lots of investors are gonna get interested into growth and go into growth. Well, at the moment, it's a big rush into growth and it doesn't end. There's a big rush into some growth. Some US stocks doesn't seem to end, but at some point that things reverse normally. So just to say that factors in general overcrowded, I think it's an exaggeration at least. So you need to look at factor by factor. For example, trends, I don't think that at the moment there's an overcrowding in trends. There was a problem in December, 2017, February, 2018, after that mass increase in trends. massive rally in stocks in the US. CTA trend followers were massively long and over leveraged equity stocks and that led into, that helps the sale of, that didn't help and that made the sale of worse in February 2018. But at the moment, if you look at the positioning of trend followers, they're rather neutral. So the market can go either way, that will not have an impact. So it really depends on the leverage of the strategy, the amount of AUM that is in the strategy and how many investors have been investing into the strategy.
